sample.title: How Chinese EVs Won Brazil ‚Äî And Left U.S. Automakers Behind
sample.description:
Brazil is the world‚Äôs sixth largest car market by volume, and the country is quickly becoming the next frontier in China‚Äôs electric vehicle expansion. Blocked from the U.S. by tariffs, China‚Äôs EV giants have turned to emerging markets like Brazil to offload their massive supply of cars. Imports from China to Brazil have skyrocketed, up nearly 100,000 vehicles in just one year, and Chinese brands like BYD now account for over 80% of electric car sales in Brazil. But the surge has U.S. automakers on edge, as Chinese companies move into markets long led by U.S. and European rivals. Watch the video above to learn more.

sample.title: How Costco quietly built a multibillion-dollar clothing empire
sample.description:
Costco has become one of the world‚Äôs biggest clothing retailers. From 2019 to 2024, it grew its annual apparel segment sales from $7 billion to $9.7 billion, a nearly 40% increase, according to estimates by GlobalData.

While the apparel segment is still a relatively small portion of Costco‚Äôs overall sales, it brings in more though its offering of popular brands and private label Kirkland Signature than some of the world‚Äôs largest apparel retailers like Abercrombie & Fitch and Old Navy.

sample.description:

Justice Secretary David Lammy said the accidental release seems to be "human error‚Äù and that an independent investigation will "fully establish the facts‚Äù.

He also confirmed new procedures for the "early removal scheme", and said foreign nationals will only be released under the scheme with the prison governor present.

The Conservatives' Robert Jenrick calls the case a "national embarrassment", saying the offender voluntarily returned to prison, but was turned away.

King Charles unveils new memorial to LGBT veterans after gay ban campaign | BBC News
sample.description:
King Charles III has unveiled a memorial to lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender military personnel after a decades-long campaign against a ban on being gay in the armed forces.
 
In his first official engagement in support of the LGBT+ community, the King visited the sculpture, named "an opened letter", at the National Memorial Arboretum in Staffordshire.
 
The memorial is dedicated to those from the LGBT+ community now serving in the forces, as well as those who served at a time when it was illegal to be gay in the military.
 
During the ban, which lasted until the year 2000, those who were gay - or were perceived to be - faced intrusive investigations, dismissal and in some cases imprisonment.
